by Goatboy on Tue May 04, 2010 11:06 am	([msg=38347]see Re: Mind control through mass media???[/msg])
Now I'm not one of those tinfoil hat people, but I definitely believe there is a conscious effort by governments, corporations, and the media companies themselves to influence the masses through the use of mass media. Think about it. You're a government in control of 300,000,000 people, many of which *coughsouthcough* are not too bright. You need to keep them under control, and you know that they enjoy watching TV for hours at a time. What do you do?The clear choice is to subtly (or no so subtly in some cases) tweak what is broadcast to suit your needs. Need more oil dependence? Promote shows criticizing the research on clean fuels. Want an accurate census? Make a series of frilly ads with lots of singing and clever slogans. Fucked up big time? Launch a vague public apology claiming you'll do better next time.It works the same way for corporations, too. If you want your product advertised, buy commercial slots on the big networks. Want your opposition to look bad? Mimic their product in your "Ours vs Generic" tests.The long and short of it is that as long as there is mass media, it will be used to control people. Next time you're watching TV (I do occasionally) keep a sharp eye out for the blatant tricks employed. Same goes for radio and just about any web site. You can't escape it. All you can do is be aware and consciously look out for it, lest you fall into the same trap.As an interesting little experiment, start actively looking for and following trends. I don't mean give in to them, but notice them. One good example I talk about a lot is American Idol. I'm sure you've probably heard of the "Pants on the ground" song. Within a week of that episode airing, I was hearing it everywhere. It just goes to show you how a program with enough viewers can have a major impact on social interaction.
Assume that everything I say is or could be a lie.1UHQ15HqBRZFykqx7mKHpYroxanLjJcUk
